   122→## New features
   123→
   126→### Arrays and unary tuples
   127→
   128→#### `P.array(pattern)`
   129→
   130→To match an array of elements, you can now use `P.array`:
   131→
   132→```ts
   133→import { match, P } from 'ts-pattern';
   134→
   135→const responsePattern = {
   136→  data: P.array({
   137→    id: P.string,
   138→    post: P.array({
   139→      title: P.string,
   140→      content: P.string,
   141→    }),
   142→  }),
   143→};
   144→
   145→fetchSomething().then((value: unknown) =>
   146→  match(value)
   147→    .with(responsePattern, (value) => {
   148→      // value: { data: { id: string, post: { title: string, content: string }[] }[] }
   149→      return value;
   150→    })
   151→    .otherwise(() => {
   152→      throw new Error('unexpected response');
   153→    })
   154→);
   155→```
   156→
   157→### Optional object properties
   158→
   159→#### `P.optional(pattern)`
   160→
   161→If you want one of the keys of your pattern to be optional, you can now use `P.optional(subpattern)`.
   162→
   163→If you `P.select()` something in an optional pattern, it's type will be infered as `T | undefined`.
   164→
   165→```ts
   166→import { match, P } from 'ts-pattern';
   167→
   168→const doSomethingWithUser = (user: User | Org) =>
   169→  match(user)
   170→    .with(
   171→      {
   172→        type: 'user',
   173→        detail: {
   174→          bio: P.optional(P.string),
   175→          socialLinks: P.optional({
   176→            twitter: P.select(),
   177→          }),
   178→        },
   179→      },
   180→      (twitterLink, value) => {
   181→        // twitterLink: string | undefined
   182→        /**
   183→         *  value.detail: {
   184→         *      bio?: string,
   185→         *      socialLinks?: {
   186→         *          twitter: string
   187→         *      }
   188→         *  }
   189→         **/
   190→      }
   191→    )
   192→    .otherwise(() => {
   193→      throw new Error('unexpected response');
   194→    });
   195→```
   196→
   197→### Union & intersection patterns
   198→
   201→#### `P.union(...patterns)`
   202→
   234→#### `P.intersection(...patterns)`
   235→
   265→### Select with sub pattern
   266→
   296→### Infer the matching types from a pattern
   297→
   298→#### `P.infer<typeof pattern>`
   299→
   300→TS-Pattern is pretty handy for parsing unknown payloads like HTTP responses. You can write a pattern for the shape you are expecting, and then use `isMatching(pattern, response)` to make sure the response has the correct shape.
   301→
   302→One limitation TS-Pattern had in its previous version was that it did not provide a way to get the TypeScript type of the value a given pattern matches. This is what `P.infer<typeof pattern>` does :)
   303→
   304→```ts
   305→const postPattern = {
   306→  title: P.string,
   307→  description: P.optional(P.string),
   308→  content: P.string,
   309→  likeCount: P.number,
   310→};
   311→
   312→type Post = P.infer<typeof postPattern>;
   313→// Post: { title: string, description?: string, content: string, likeCount: number }
   314→
   315→const userPattern = {
   316→  name: P.string,
   317→  postCount: P.number,
   318→  bio: P.optional(P.string),
   319→  posts: P.optional(P.array(postPattern)),
   320→};
   321→
   322→type User = P.infer<typeof userPattern>;
   323→// User: { name: string, postCount: number, bio?: string, posts?: Post[]  }
   324→
   325→const isUserList = isMatching(P.array(userPattern));
   326→
   327→const res = await fetchUsers();
   328→
   329→if (isUserList(res)) {
   330→  // res: User
   331→}
   332→```
   333→
   334→### New type specific wildcards
   335→
   336→#### `P.symbol`
   337→
   338→`P.symbol` is a wildcard pattern matching any **symbol**.
   339→
   340→```ts
   341→match(Symbol('Hello'))
   342→  .with(P.symbol, () => 'this is a symbol!')
   343→  .exhaustive();
   344→```
   345→
   346→#### `P.bigint`
   347→
